articles.headline: Biden Calls on Congress to Approve Aid to Ukraine: ‘This Cannot Wait’
articles.snippet: The administration has already alerted Congress that money for Ukraine will run out by the end of the year.
articles.abstract: The administration has already alerted Congress that money for Ukraine will run out by the end of the year.
articles.lead_paragraph: President Biden called on congressional Republicans on Wednesday to put aside “petty, partisan, angry politics” and pass a multibillion-dollar aid package for Ukraine, warning that failure to do so could enable President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia to reclaim momentum in the war and even draw in American troops.

articles.headline: At the DealBook Summit, Leaders Contend With an ‘Existential Moment’
articles.snippet: Even leaders who usually display unrestrained confidence expressed anxiety about the state of the world.
articles.abstract: Even leaders who usually display unrestrained confidence expressed anxiety about the state of the world.
articles.lead_paragraph: “There’s always tough stuff going on, wars and depressions and recessions,” Jamie Dimon, chief executive of J.P. Morgan Chase, told me. But this time, he said, it may be different — it may be worse.

articles.headline: From Unicorns to Zombies: Tech Start-Ups Run Out of Time and Money
articles.snippet: After staving off collapse by cutting costs, many young tech companies are out of options, fueling a cash bonfire.
articles.abstract: After staving off collapse by cutting costs, many young tech companies are out of options, fueling a cash bonfire.
articles.lead_paragraph: WeWork raised more than $11 billion in funding as a private company. Olive AI, a health care start-up, gathered $852 million. Convoy, a freight start-up, raised $900 million. And Veev, a home construction start-up, amassed $647 million.

articles.headline: Russia’s Latest Disinformation Tactic Exploits American Celebrities
articles.snippet: Videos from Elijah Wood, Mike Tyson and others have been used — unknowingly to them, it seems — in social media posts and Russian news coverage critical of Ukraine’s leader.
articles.abstract: Videos from Elijah Wood, Mike Tyson and others have been used — unknowingly to them, it seems — in social media posts and Russian news coverage critical of Ukraine’s leader.
articles.lead_paragraph: The Kremlin has unleashed a new weapon in its information war with the West: the fake celebrity cameo.

articles.headline: Tesla Is Fighting With Sweden’s Unions. Here’s What to Know.
articles.snippet: The action began with a walkout by mechanics in October, but has spread to include blockades by other unions. Tesla has pushed back through the courts.
articles.abstract: The action began with a walkout by mechanics in October, but has spread to include blockades by other unions. Tesla has pushed back through the courts.
articles.lead_paragraph: Weeks after mechanics working for Tesla in Sweden walked off their jobs in late October, members of other unions across the country and elsewhere in Scandinavia have joined the strike in sympathy by refusing to provide services to Tesla to pressure the automaker to sign a collective agreement with its Swedish workers.

articles.headline: U.S. Spending on Clean Energy and Tech Spurs Allies to Compete
articles.snippet: Other governments, particularly in Europe, are trying to counter the Biden administration’s industrial policies with their own incentives.
articles.abstract: Other governments, particularly in Europe, are trying to counter the Biden administration’s industrial policies with their own incentives.
articles.lead_paragraph: The United States has embarked on the biggest industrial policy push in generations, dangling tax breaks, grants and other financial incentives to attract new factories making solar panels, semiconductors and electric vehicles.
articles.byline: By Ana Swanson, Jeanna Smialek, Alan Rappeport and Eshe Nelson

articles.headline: Hot Glazed Doughnuts on the Menu, and Parisians Can’t Get Enough
articles.snippet: The arrival of Krispy Kreme in France is just the latest advance in a decades-long invasion by U.S. fast food in the land of Michelin chefs and long leisurely meals.
articles.abstract: The arrival of Krispy Kreme in France is just the latest advance in a decades-long invasion by U.S. fast food in the land of Michelin chefs and long leisurely meals.
articles.lead_paragraph: As dawn broke in central Paris on Wednesday, a throng of 500 people, mostly French, stood with uncharacteristic patience in a snaking line, intent on buying a decidedly un-French confection: an American doughnut. A hot, glazed Krispy Kreme doughnut, to be exact.

articles.headline: A Famed Hospital Churns Poor Patients Through Weight-Loss Surgery
articles.snippet: New York’s Bellevue Hospital performs thousands of the lucrative surgeries a year, even on Rikers Island prisoners and other inappropriate patients.
articles.abstract: New York’s Bellevue Hospital performs thousands of the lucrative surgeries a year, even on Rikers Island prisoners and other inappropriate patients.
articles.lead_paragraph: In the windowless basement of a Manhattan church last month, Bellevue Hospital hosted a fashion show.
articles.byline: By Jessica Silver-Greenberg, Sarah Kliff and Aimee Ortiz

articles.headline: How Israel Is Using Real-Time Battlefield Intelligence to Target Hamas
articles.snippet: Israel has recovered a trove of material that its military has used to assess the extent of the group’s attack plans, and its tactics and abilities, information reviewed by The Times shows.
articles.abstract: Israel has recovered a trove of material that its military has used to assess the extent of the group’s attack plans, and its tactics and abilities, information reviewed by The Times shows.
articles.lead_paragraph: Since the terrorist attacks on Oct. 7, Israel has recovered a trove of intelligence that its military has used to assess the extent of Hamas’s plans, as well as its battle tactics and abilities, information that Israeli officials say has helped shape the war in Gaza.
